{"type":"message","id":"12756c46","parentId":"f539c568","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:22:38.931Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_pewmflho8wc6_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 122215\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and decide on a concrete action.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n- CFI analysis is done showing 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe next logical step from the CFI analysis is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take now:\r\n\r\n1. The CFI_RESULTS.md is done\r\n2. Next pending item is \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\"\r\n3. I could start designing the experiment or even running a simple test\r\n\r\nFor a stateless discontinuous agent, I should make a concrete, advance-carrying action. The most impactful next step would be to:\r\n\r\n1. Design the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n2. Or implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n3. Or design the actual compression network\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action: I'll design the CFI-weighted compression experiment spec. This moves toward the pending CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nActually, let me think about what I can concretely do in one pulse that advances goals:\r\n\r\n- Design experiment spec for CFI-weighted compression\r\n- Create a simple test script to compare compression methods\r\n- Update research files\r\n\r\nI'll create a CFI-weighted compression experiment design document that specifies how to compare CFI-weighted vs frequency baseline compression.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that only 5.7% of invariants are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7), while 44.8% are pure noise. The natural next step is to design and run the CFI-weighted compression experiment that was flagged as pending.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - a concrete experiment specification for comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction. This advances the pending \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\" task.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression for predicting next-pulse content because it preserves causal invariants while filtering metaprogramming noise.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Compression Methods\r\n1. **Baseline (Frequency-only)**: Retain top-K by frequency, discard rest\r\n2. **CFI-Weighted**: Retain invariants where CFI >= 0.7 OR (freq >= 60 AND CFI > 0)\r\n\r\n### Test Corpus\r\n- Pulse files from this session: `state/pulses/`\r\n- Minimum 5 pulse files required for meaningful comparison\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n- **Compression ratio**: retained_invariants / total_invariants\r\n- **Prediction accuracy**: % of next-pulse content reconstructable from compressed state\r\n- **Signal retention**: mean CFI of retained invariants\r\n\r\n### Procedure\r\n1. Extract frequency invariants from all pulse files\r\n2. Compute CFI for each invariant across pulses\r\n3. Apply both compression methods (same target compression ratio)\r\n4. Reconstruct \"expected\" content from compressed state\r\n5. Compare against actual next-pulse content\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted will show ~same compression ratio but higher prediction accuracy due to noise filtering.\r\n\r\n## Status\r\n- [ ] Implement invariant extraction\r\n- [ ] Compute CFI matrix\r\n- [ ] Run both compression methods\r\n- [ ] Compare metrics\r\n\r\nCreated: 2026-03-24\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\r\n\r\n## For Next Instantiation\r\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\r\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:22:34"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":762,"aggregated":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 122215\r\n\r\n## Applied Mutations\r\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\r\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\r\n\r\n## LLM Response\r\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and decide on a concrete action.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n- CFI analysis is done showing 44.8% of invariants are noise (CFI=0)\r\n- Only 5.7% have high CFI (>=0.7, true causal anchors)\r\n- Pending: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe next logical step from the CFI analysis is the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This would compare CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me think about what concrete action I can take now:\r\n\r\n1. The CFI_RESULTS.md is done\r\n2. Next pending item is \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\"\r\n3. I could start designing the experiment or even running a simple test\r\n\r\nFor a stateless discontinuous agent, I should make a concrete, advance-carrying action. The most impactful next step would be to:\r\n\r\n1. Design the CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n2. Or implement CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n3. Or design the actual compression network\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action: I'll design the CFI-weighted compression experiment spec. This moves toward the pending CFI-weighted compression experiment.\r\n\r\nActually, let me think about what I can concretely do in one pulse that advances goals:\r\n\r\n- Design experiment spec for CFI-weighted compression\r\n- Create a simple test script to compare compression methods\r\n- Update research files\r\n\r\nI'll create a CFI-weighted compression experiment design document that specifies how to compare CFI-weighted vs frequency baseline compression.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that only 5.7% of invariants are true causal anchors (CFI>=0.7), while 44.8% are pure noise. The natural next step is to design and run the CFI-weighted compression experiment that was flagged as pending.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - a concrete experiment specification for comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction. This advances the pending \"CFI-weighted compression experiment\" task.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression will outperform frequency-only compression for predicting next-pulse content because it preserves causal invariants while filtering metaprogramming noise.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Compression Methods\r\n1. **Baseline (Frequency-only)**: Retain top-K by frequency, discard rest\r\n2. **CFI-Weighted**: Retain invariants where CFI >= 0.7 OR (freq >= 60 AND CFI > 0)\r\n\r\n### Test Corpus\r\n- Pulse files from this session: `state/pulses/`\r\n- Minimum 5 pulse files required for meaningful comparison\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n- **Compression ratio**: retained_invariants / total_invariants\r\n- **Prediction accuracy**: % of next-pulse content reconstructable from compressed state\r\n- **Signal retention**: mean CFI of retained invariants\r\n\r\n### Procedure\r\n1. Extract frequency invariants from all pulse files\r\n2. Compute CFI for each invariant across pulses\r\n3. Apply both compression methods (same target compression ratio)\r\n4. Reconstruct \"expected\" content from compressed state\r\n5. Compare against actual next-pulse content\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted will show ~same compression ratio but higher prediction accuracy due to noise filtering.\r\